data.title: Downtown Waterloo bridges opening delayed until fall, no pedestrian use until 2025
data.meta_description: The Park Avenue bridge was supposed to be open for traffic in July and the 11th Street bridge was estimated to be finished around October.
data.text:
WATERLOO — Both downtown bridges under construction are now set to open sometime in the fall, but pedestrians will not be able to use them until 2025.

The Park Avenue bridge was supposed to be open for traffic in July and the 11th Street bridge was estimated to be finished around October. City Engineer Jamie Knutson told the City Council on Monday both are now expected to open later this year.

His announcement was met with groans from several residents at the meeting.

More disappointment came after Knutson said pedestrian railings won’t be delivered until 2025. He said another entity placed a large order right before the city resulting in the delays. The city could not order railings until the bridge’s decks were poured — which happened last year.

Without pedestrian railings, the city can’t allow walkers and bikers to use the bridge for safety reasons. Knutson said the city plans to talk to the Iowa Department of Transportation to find a temporary solution. Vehicles would still be allowed on the bridges.

Both bridges closed in 2022 for a total reconstruction. They were expected to be completed in fall of 2023.

In 2019, Waterloo received a $12.5 million federal grant to pay for the replacement of both the 11th Street and Park Avenue bridges. The city allocated $7.5 million to the project. In 2015, the city stated the Park Avenue bridge had deteriorated. The 11th Street bridge also is in declining condition.

The bridges were built in 1938 and 1953, respectively. Park Avenue’s bridge was the oldest of the eight major city-owned bridges crossing the river.

Once the projects are done, the city shouldn’t have to replace another major bridge for at least two decades, Knutson said previously. Pavement is expected to last 50 to 70 years.

The new bridges are supposed to prevent future flooding and increase aesthetics downtown.
